sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1184000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Eric Pederson
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
KillerRed is a red fluorescent protein that produces reactive oxygen species (ROS) in the presence of yellow-orange light (540-585 nm). KillerRed is engineered from Aequorea victoria GFP (avGFP) to be phototoxic. It has been shown that KillerRed produces superoxide radical anions by reacting with water. Superoxide reacts with the chromophore of KillerRed, causing it to become dark, which ultimately gives rise to a bleaching effect. KillerRed is spectrally similar to mRFP1 with a similar brightness. KillerRed is oligomeric and may form large aggregates.
This sequence is codon optimized for mammalian cells and has 14 rare proline codons for E. coli (CCC) and one rare arginine codon (AGA). Codon optimization should be taken into consideration if large amounts of the protein are required. Expression on a high-copy plasmid has produced detectable fluorescent signal, however.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This sequence is not codon optimized for E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Engineered from avGFP. Provided by the Bruchez lab at Carnegie Mellon

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1497021
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Naringenin sensor (FdeR) with mKate as reporter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Sascha Hein, Niklas Hummel, Sebastian Barthel, Thomas Dohmen
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: We modified the naringenin biosensor from Siedler et al. by elimination of one EcoRI restriction site and by changing the native ribosomal binding site into the strong RBS Bba_B0034. Based on this reporter protein and 3 different fluorescence proteins, we designed 3 new biosensors for in vivo detection and determination of naringenin. The natural source of FdeR is Herbaspirillum seropedicae. You can use our reporter for measuring naringenin concentrations in your samples. Depending on which fluorophor you want to detect, you can use one of three biosensors: GFP fluorescence K1497020 mKate (DsRed variant) fluorescence K1497021 CFP fluorescence K1497022

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1926013
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: The mCHERRY UNIT: mCherry flanked by Vox
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Xinyi Liu
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part is the mCHERRY UNIT of cyclebow system including a degradation tag named DBOX, a fluorescent gene mCherry and an sv40 terminator flanked by homodromous recognition site of recombinase VIKA named Vox. The whole part can be cut off by VIKA.
You may use this part to:
1) Provide fluorescent red which can be quickly cut off by transient transfecting recombinase gene into nucleus;
2) Use it as a part of the flp-out system[5].
5. Voutev, R. and E.J. Hubbard, A "FLP-Out" system for controlled gene expression in Caenorhabditis elegans. Genetics, 2008. 180(1): p. 103-19.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: None
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequence of Vox and DBOX was retrieved from Addgene and got through denovo synthesis. mCHERRY and sv40 terminator were got from commercial plasmid: pentry dcas9 mcherry bira and pentry nls GFP/pcdna3.1, respectfully.
